The United Nations and Turkey <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30828116.26898/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vbWFya2V0cy9jb21tb2RpdGllcy9ydXNzaWFuLW9mZmljaWFsLWJsYWNrLXNlYS1ncmFpbi1kZWFsLWV4dGVuZGVkLTYwLWRheXMtdGFzcy0yMDIzLTAzLTE0Lz91dG1fc291cmNlPWRhaWx5YnJpZWY/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7Bc0018f0d" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">mediated a second day of talks (Reuters)</a> today to try to extend a deal under which Russia allows Ukraine to export grain and other food products from its ports in the Black Sea. Moscow said it would <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30828116.26898/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTQvd2hlYXQtc3RlYWR5LWFzLXVrcmFpbmUtcmVidWZmcy1ydXNzaWFuLW9mZmVyLW9uLWdyYWluLWRlYWw_dXRtX3NvdXJjZT10d2l0dGVyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1zb2NpYWxmbG93LW9yZ2FuaWMmdXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9YnVzaW5lc3MmY21waWQ9c29jaWFsZmxvdy10d2l0dGVyLWJ1c2luZXNzJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09c29jaWFsJnNyZWY9dnhTelZEUDA/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7B78ea0287" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">allow a sixty-day renewal (Bloomberg)</a> of the deal, which Kyiv <a href="https://link.cfr.org/click/30828116.26898/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvcnVzc2lhLW9wZW4tdG8tNjAtZGF5LWV4dGVuc2lvbi1vZi11a3JhaW5lLWdyYWluLWRlYWwtdGFzcy1zYXlzP3NyZWY9dnhTelZEUDAmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1kYWlseWJyaWVm/5e137cf6ecf12a133a10a3b7B54fd5b01" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">rejected (Bloomberg)</a> on grounds that the broader agreement allows for extensions of at least 120 days. 
</p><p> </p><p>
The deal signed in July 2022 has brought down global food prices that had spiked to record highs following Russia’s invasion of Ukraine. Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov said the deal does not address Russia’s concerns that Western sanctions have indirectly hurt its agriculture exports. Grain futures have fluctuated amid conflicting reports of an extension, and wheat importers in the Middle East and North Africa are stocking up on the crop ahead of the deal’s potential expiration.
